article.headline: Lackluster Rutgers clings on to lead over Pepperdine
article.story:
PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- C. Vivian Stringer decided to do a little experimenting in No. 6 Rutgers' game against Pepperdine, and it showed.

Matee Ajavon scored 16 points and Rutgers won its fifth straight game with a lackluster 55-45 victory Wednesday night.

Epiphanny Prince and Rashidat Junaid added 12 each for Rutgers (10-2), which didn't pull away until Ajavon, Prince and Essence Carson led a 12-2 spurt in the final 10 minutes.

The biggest change for Stringer was playing Kia Vaughn and Junaid together.

"We are experimenting with some things, and it is important to see if we can play two big people and [we're] trying to see statistically what two big people will represent as far as rebounding," said the coach, whose team was outrebounded 35-32. "I thought we did a pretty good job."

Daphanie Kennedy and Katie Menton scored 10 points each to lead Pepperdine (5-7), which finished 0-3 on an East Coast swing that also included losses to Coppin State and George Washington.

After Teena Wickett hit a layup to get Pepperdine within three with 12:17 to play, Rutgers took over in avenging an overtime loss to the Waves early last season.

Prince started the run with a jumper and Ajavon added two layups in a 28-second span, the second coming off a steal for a 40-31 lead.

"I am used to seeing plays like that from Matee," Carson said. "She's a big-time player and she makes big plays at crucial moments in the game. We definitely needed it. Any steal is a plus for us, especially when we convert off of it. We definitely needed something to pull the momentum on our side."

After Teiosha George made a layup for Pepperdine, Carson hit two free throws and a jumper and Prince converted a layup with just under 6 minutes to play to put Rutgers ahead 46-33.

Pepperdine, which had 17 turnovers, never got closer than nine points the rest of the way.

Carson finished with five points and became the 26th member of Rutgers' 1,000-point club. She was making her first appearance since Dec. 10 after being sidelined with a stress fracture.

"It felt good to be back," Carson said. "Sitting out and just watching the game didn't sit too well with me, especially with any type of competitiveness. And scoring 1,000 points, I didn't know about it before. I was wondering why everyone was clapping."

Both teams struggled from beyond the 3-point arc, the Scarlet Knights going 1-for-11. Menton was 3-of-10 from long range for Pepperdine, but the rest of the team was 0-for-7.

Rutgers announced before the game that freshman Khadijah Rushdan will miss the rest of the season with a torn anterior cruciate ligament in her right knee. She was hurt in Sunday's win over Temple.
